<!-- Introduction to Australia -->
<pre style="text-align:center; color:black; width:700px; height:75px; padding: 4px; margin: auto; background-color: #4682B4;"><b>Australia</b> is one of the largest countries yet smallest continent on Earth, lying between the 
Pacific and Indian ocean in the Southern Hemisphere. Globally, it is famous for its <b>natural 
wonders, wide open spaces, iconic infrastructure</b> and is widely known for Australia's Outback and 
its conditions. These icons have helped shaped Australia in the modern world and have grown the 
country in many ways. </pre>
<br>
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/88/Flag_of_Australia_%28converted%29.svg/1200px-Flag_of_Australia_%28converted%29.svg.png" alt="Flag of Australia" title="Flag of Australia" width="600" height="300">
<br>
<pre style="text-align:center; color:black; width:700px; height:150px; padding: 4px; margin: auto; background-color: #4682B4;">
Most of the interior of the continent is arid to semi-desert and droughts because of low rainfall. 
Australia is rich in mineral deposits including gold, coal, and iron ore. The coastal areas of 
Australia have the best soils for agriculture; therefore, areas around the states of Australia 
such as Perth, Adelaide, Melbourne, Sydney, and Brisbane have grown rich in agriculture 
and food production and are the main agricultural centers.

Not only the the states of Australia rich in agriculture, it is also rich in
infrastructure that makes itself an icon of Australia. Australia has a wide variety of mega 
structures 
</pre>

